Datasource


The original data set is mainly from Cata et al.Â âBlood Storage Duration and Biochemical Recurrence of Cancer after Radical Prostate- ctomyâ. Mayo Clin Proc 2011; 86(2): 120-127.

From the description on package website: âThis data set contains data on 316 men who had undergone radical prostatectomy and received transfusion during or within 30 days of the surgical procedure and had available prostate serum antigen (PSA) follow-up data. The main exposure of interest was RBC storage duration group.â

To be able to tidy, adjust and explore, the group received a dataset that was not in a tidy format anymore.

We started by exploring the data, and quickly noticed that:

1) the dataset did not contain 316 rows, but 672
2) the column names did not have optimized naming
3) some rows contained variables, and some variables were observations #untidy!!


Based on this, we started tidying so that every column became a variable and every row became an observation.

Tidy the data

To tidy the âexam.dataset.txtâ, we had to:

  • remove duplicated rows
  • rename columns that contain spaces, punctuation signs or start with numbers (e.g.âX1_Ageâ to âAgeâ)
  • rename columns to more intuitive names (e.g.Â âUnitsâ to âAllogeneic.unitsâ)
  • separate columns (e.g.Â âsubjectâ to âsubjectâ + âHospitalâ)
  • reshape values in columns including various measurements (e.g.Â âTimeToRecurrence-unitâ into days)

    Then the tidy dataset was saved as âtidy_exam_dataset.txtâ

Adjust/manipulate/wrangle the data

To adjust the âtidy_exam_dataset.txtâ we had to:

  • remove unnecessary columns from the dataframe (âAAâ, âbGSâ âBNplusâ and âOrganConfined)
  • change variable types (âsubjectâ from character to numeric)
  • create a set of new columns (e.g.Â ârecurrenceâ to return the values Yes or No)
  • change and arrange the order of some columns
  • organize the R code in a pipe
  • join an additional dataset to the tidied dataset

    Now, the new file contains 316 number of observations and 21 number of variables.
    The tidied and manipulated dataset was saved in a new file âtidy_adjust_exam_dataset.txtâ and the codebook was updated.

Exploratory data analysis (EDA) of the data

To explore the data, we did the following:

  • count columns with missing variables (number of columns containing NA = 7)
  • stratify the data by a categorical column (âTimeToRecurrence_daysâ grouped by âT.stageâ)
  • calculate minimum and maximum levels, mean and sd for several conditions and create a table

Create plots

In this chapter we would like to present some of the plots we created to answer questions given in the exam description.

Correlation matrix
First we checked if there were any correlated measurements whitin the variables by computing a correlation matrix.
Here, the numbers tell the correlation, and the color indicates if it is negative(red) or positive(blue), and the opacity of the number indicates the degree of correlation (strong color=strong correlation):



Is there a relation between PVol and TVol
We calculated the correlation and found that there is a negative correlation between PVol and TVol of -0,21, meaning that for every 1 TVol increases, PVol decreases with 0.21. This is illustrated with the regression line in the plot below:




Does the distribution of PreopPSA depend on T.Stage?
We computed a Welch Two Sample t-test, showing a p-value of 0,01, indicating there is a significant difference in meanPreopPSA between the T.Stage groups. The distribution of observations are illustrated in the boxplot below:




Does the distribution of PVol depend on sGS
First we visually inspected the distribution of sGS groups PVols, respectively in a boxplot (se below). Next, we conducted ANOVA analysis which turned P-value (Pr(>F)): 0.00434, indicating strong statistical significance. This suggests that the differences in PVol across the sGS groups are statistically significant and unlikely to have occurred by chance.




Does the distribution of TVol depend on `sGS?

We computed a plot (see below) and calculated ANOVA which turned a p-value (Pr(>F)) of 3.39e-11 - . The p-value indicates the probability of observing such a strong association between sGS and TVol by chance alone, under the null hypothesis that sGS has no effect on TVol. The p-value is extremely small, providing strong evidence against the null hypothesis, suggesting that the differences in TVol across the groups defined by sGS are highly statistically significant




Are there more T.Stage == 2 in the group with PreopTherapy == 1 than in the group PreopTherapy == 0?
We plotted the counts of T.Stage == 2 by PreopTherapy group, and found there were most T.Stage==2 in the group âPreopTherapy == 0â. Perhaps this cpould indicate that those who didnt recieve preoperative therapy had hinger T.Stage (more severe disease).




Analyzing the data


Was the time to recurrence different for various RBC.Age.Group levels?

The mean time to recurrence in group 1,2 and 3 was 238, 215 and 238, respectively. There were no numeric difference in time to recurrence in the RBC.Age.Group` 1 and 3. However, Group 2 showed some difference and we applied statistical tests to investigate if the difference was statistically significant. We visually inspected the data by histogram and found that it was not normally distributed. Using Anova and Kruskal-Wallis test, both indicated that the difference is not statistically significant with p values of 0,775 and 0,592, respectively.




Was the time to recurrence different for various T.Stage levels?
The time to recurrence was clearly different between the two T-stage groups. For patients with T-stage 1 the mean time to recurrence was 246 (Std.dev 204) days. For patients with T-Stage 2 the mean time to recurrence was only 150 (std.dev 159) days.
Time to recurrence is 15 % longer in those with T stage 1 than T stage 2.
The difference can also be visualized by a box-plot.

Analyzing the two groups with a Kruskal-Wallis test, the difference is highly statistically significant with a p-value of 0,0048.

Did having AdjRadTherapy affect time to recurrence?
Only 1 out og 316 patient had âAdjRadTherapyâ. The mean time to recurrence for patients not having âAdjRadTherapyâ was 231 days while the time to recurrence for the patient having âAdjRadTherapyâ was 59 days. There is not enough power to draw any conclusions here.



Did those that had recurrence had also larger TVol values than those without recurrence?
Patients having âTvolâ = 3 had the highest insidense of recurrence;
- 2 out of 64 (3 %) patients with Tvol = 1 had Recurrence.
-19 out of 153 (7%) patienst with Tvol = 2 had Recurence.
-30 out of 93 (20%) patienst with Tvol = 3 had Recurrence.
